If your string parsing produces some dynamically allocated strings, then you could just copy it to a history array at the end of the loop. 

At the next loop pass you have access to both, the new values in arr and the previous values in history. The first loop pass is something special, you have to be careful, because in this case you do not have any history values.

To be able to have self-containing example, instead of a real parsing the code just creates dynamically some strings. 

In code it could look like this:

    #include &lt;stdio.h&gt;
    #include &lt;stdlib.h&gt;
    #include &lt;string.h&gt;
    
    
    char *some_str(int counter, int index) {
        char *result = malloc(32);
        sprintf(result, &quot;arbitrary %d_%d&quot;, counter, index);
        return result;
    }
    
    #define NUM 2
    
    int main() {
        char *history[NUM];
        memset(history, &#39;\0&#39;, sizeof history);
    
        int counter = 0;
        while(1) {
            char *arr[NUM];
    
            //fill arr with some dynamically allocated strings
            for(int i = 0; i &lt; NUM; i++) {
                arr[i] = some_str(counter, i);
            }
    
            //here you can access both, new arr and history values at the same tme
            for(int i = 0; i &lt; NUM; i++) {
                char *hist =  history[i];
                if(hist == NULL) {
                    hist = &quot;none&quot;;
                }
                printf(&quot;history[%d]=&#39;%s&#39; and arr[%d]=&#39;%s&#39;\n&quot;, i, hist, i, arr[i]);
            }
            printf(&quot;\n&quot;);
    
            //free current history if available and copy arr
            for(int i = 0; i &lt; NUM; i++) {
                if(history[i]) {
                    free(history[i]);
                }
